                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d306">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/3585: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-11-19T18:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 19, 1921—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 19—9:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>409. My 403, November 16th, noon [<hi rend="italic">midnight</hi>]. Continue,
                    payments by the two banks virtually ceased, governmental agencies still
                    accepting notes. Hsu Un Yan [<hi rend="italic">Hsu En-yuan?</hi>
                    <note n="32" xml:id="d306fn32">Vice President of the Chinese American Bank of
                        Commerce.</note>] informs me this is the most severe panic on record. All
                    silver has disappeared from circulation, business at a standstill, Cabinet
                    discussing moratorium.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
